title.narrative: QUALITY MATERNAL/NEONATAL/CHILD HEALTH SERVICES

description.narrative: By 2019, health facilities are equipped for providing quality maternal, neonatal and child health services, including gender responsive adolescent health services., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Hiv Prevention, Hiv Prevention (Covid), Immunization, Immunization (Covid), Maternal And Newborn Health, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022,boys and girls aged 0-59 months, adolescents and women (especially those living in the most disadvantaged communities) have access to basic services, use packages of multisectoral high-impact, gender-sensitive interventions (health /HIV, nutrition, WASH) and adopt appropriate behaviours.

title.narrative: By 2019, health facilities are equipped for providing quality maternal, neonatal and child health services, including gender responsive adolescent health services.

description.narrative: Thanks to the capacity-building of care providers and the provision of equipment in the 40 convergence municipalities, the quality of maternal, newborn and child health services improved in 2019. Indeed, coverage of equipped health facilities increased from 56% in 2018 to 65% in 2019 and made it possible to assist with 12,862 deliveries. The national immunization service offer increased from 417 to 1,265 following the fitting-out of 848 health posts with solar refrigerators. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/12/2019
